snippet.textDisplay:
@XxSpaceCakexX Well it's not a trick, it's just how music used to work in games back then, even the original super mario theme and the donkey kong country tracks on the snes all use soundfont based music, it's just that the nes was limited to mostly beeping noises.

However, there are a number of ds games which use actual audio, but often the tracks are very compressed as a space saving measure (such as Elite Beat Agents or The World Ends With You) so they dont always have the best sound quality.
snippet.textOriginal:
@XxSpaceCakexX Well it's not a trick, it's just how music used to work in games back then, even the original super mario theme and the donkey kong country tracks on the snes all use soundfont based music, it's just that the nes was limited to mostly beeping noises.

However, there are a number of ds games which use actual audio, but often the tracks are very compressed as a space saving measure (such as Elite Beat Agents or The World Ends With You) so they dont always have the best sound quality.

snippet.textDisplay:
Probably not too impressive when you consider the songs are stored as midis (or a similar format) rather than actual audio files. The difference is like playing a cd vs having a musician sit in front of you and play off of sheet music; the instrument is a pre-programmed sound that's part of a "soundfont", the system itself is the musician, and the sheet music tells the musician how to play the song in real time. Because all you need to save are the "instruments" and "sheet music" the actual complex audio data that makes files like mp3 so big can be safely ignored, allowing you to get more bang for your buck in terms of storage.

Don't get me wrong, the amount of songs and their length are still impressive, but your comment seems to imply you think it was because of hardware storage limitations (for context, some guy ripped the midis for the sequel Explorers games and they come out at around 1.30 mb in size: https://psycommando.tumblr.com/post/105768826462/pokémon-mystery-dungeon-explorers-of-sky-full )

snippet.textDisplay:
An Average Pichu if i had to make a top 5 i think it would be:
5. Zinnia battle theme (OR/AS)
4. Dialga/Palkia battle theme (diamond/pearl)
3. Temporal Tower (PMD2)
2. Dialga's Fight to the Finish (PMD2)
Those 2 sound very similar but i think it's still important to separate them from each other because dialga's fight to the finish is extremely powerful and great because of that but temporal tower is so deep and emotional. when it starts playing after grovyle's death you feel like you're flying through the dungeon and that there's just no way to fail.
And the top step would go to sky tower as i said. this is so great. it's just complete. it has everything. the game came out 10 years ago and i'm still listening to it regularly. just incredible! it gives you hope, gives you that "one last time" or "let's finish this" feeling but has still such a great rhythm that you want to dance to it.
but of course 5 songs are far too few to acknowledge all the great pokemon soundtracks out there. even in the first mystery dungeon i could give you about 10 to 15 that are absolutely awesome. but as i said if i had to break it down to 5 these would be in it.
BTW have a look at the "dialga's fight to the finish remix" on the channel of LOrbSheddy. it's the best remix out there in my opinion :)

snippet.textDisplay: Oh wow this song :') god I remember playing the game and getting to the final dungeon for the first time and this song haunted me for so long after, it really conveys the emotions of the main story's climax, I mean the beat is quite upbeat as a lot of PMD tracks are, but the violins and the flutes (I think, Im not so good with instruments), and the bit where the drum beat disappears and just leaves the violin to play that haunting tune really gives this track a sense of destiny and finality, with even a hint of melancholy realusation that this will be the last adventure with your partner pokemon....I could genuinely mong out to this song all day, its a great piece of music <3

snippet.textDisplay: Did anyone else end up preferring the Mystery Dungeon spin off games to the actual series? Beautifully crafted sprites and areas, excellent music, gameplay that I enjoyed more than the standard turn based Pokemon setup, wonderfully written stories and relatively believable dialogue. Simply perfection.

snippet.textDisplay: This was me. The first Pokemon game I got to play when I had a GBA was Sapphire, then Fire Red then Emerald. They were fun but I didn't really play them too much and they didn't really become my fave GBA games. But when I tried Pokemon Mystery Dungeon it has quickly become my favorite game! Maybe it's partly because I like roguelikes, and one of the first RPGs I've played is Chocobo's Dungeon 2 which is a roguelike much like PMD, and also partly because I fell in love with PMD's story which I thought was waaaay better than Emerald's.

snippet.textDisplay: 100% I think explorers is the best pokémon game by a wide margin. Type coverage, and exploiting weaknesses with relatively limited power points makes the standard rock paper scissors-type combat much more interesting than the main series games in my opinion. Not to mention that many of the dungeons in the games are very difficult, something all of the main series pokémon games lack without severe self imposed restrictions.

snippet.textDisplay: I remember the first time I heard this soundtrack in PMD:BRT, I was stunned at how intense yet delicate it was. It's incredible how at first listen it sounds very happy and joyful, but following the story, it carries a much deeper, somber note that just played with my emotions time and time again. The idea that you and your best friend were to venture where no one else could, to the sky, where you knew very well that it could be your last adventure, and that your return mattered not, was incredibly powerful. If you succeeded, the world continues. You and your best friend must save the world, at your own loss, and you know you won't make it back. To this day every time I listen to it, I remember the amount of times I had to repeat the dungeon to beat Rayquaza, but also that I didn't mind, because it gave me another opportunity to hear its fantastic music. I will admit that the first few times, it made me tear up, but I truly appreciate the incredible emotional influence that the story and track evoke. This soundtrack is simply magnificent. Nothing less.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'll tell you the feeling I got from this theme when I heard it. There is this certain sensation of inevitability and great scope to this song. In the story, you and your best friend are going into the world of the clouds, and you fully expect that you might never make it back alive. And yet, what you are doing is greater than yourselves. Whether you return or not doesn't matter because by succeeding, the WORLD will continue on. No one else can do what you are setting out to do. There's no turning back. This is why you've been brought to this world. It's time to save everyone by any means possible.

It's a testament to the absolutely unparalleled storytelling ability of all three of the Mystery Dungeon games (I say "three" not counting variants or the Wiiware PMD). I truly and wholeheartedly say that simply through the emotions of events like this, the PMD games have by far the most gripping and touching storylines I've EVER experienced in video games. And seeing as I've been around since the early days of the NES, that means something.

snippet.textDisplay:
I also cried a lot during the ending song of Blue Rescue Team, and this song here makes me remember a lot...
I also cried very much during the dissappearance of my character at the Time Tower, in Explorers of the Sky.

But I just don't like the story of Gates to Infinity...Yes, I felt sad at the end of the story, but I can't even remember it. This was touching, but far less than the previouses games. I'm under the impression that they just have made another storyline with Kyurem, in order to respect the spirit of the PMD games, and then that's all. You can't even recruit all Pokemon like before. It's so much casualized that I had very fex fun playing it, and just a little sadness at the end. The only thing that I felt during the credits was nothing. I was just thinking "Am I not supposed to cry? Is it not sad?". But I think I couldn't identify myself with the character in the game. And this is what makes this game, in my point of view, the worst of the three PMDs.

It's not that the Pokemon are unbeatable, it's the entire presentation of the monster house itself, a ton of Pokemon showering from the floor above and the music changing.  The music is definitely the worst part, especially in dungeons when I listen to the background music for fun (Sky Tower, etc.) and then all of a sudden the song changes, it scared the crap out of me as a kid and still does (childhood trauma).  

I wish I could mod the game so the music doesn't change in a monster house...

snippet.textDisplay:
You are climbing up a tower made of clouds in an attempt to save a world that is not your own, with the realization that you shall have to leave your new best friend and everything you can remember, into a world that knows you but remains a mystery to you. A realization that no matter that even if you can stay, everyone who ever knew you in one world will miss you forever. This sorrow is what makes this music the most important piece of music I have heard in my life.
Fact.

It has a certain majesty in that you are in a tower made of clouds, high above the earth below.

Nostalgia.... the memories.  This game is probably the best spin-off, no the best pokemon GAME ever. I mean, the challenges, fighting huge legendaries at your 20s, and listening to awesome music. After I beat Rayquaza, not knowing what was going to happen next, I shed a tear, not wanting it to end. But my wish came true, and I still had the post-game to complete.

Even though this isn't as popular as the others, Pokemon mystery dungeon 1, I'll never forget!

snippet.textDisplay:
This is the only thing that I feel PMD 2 was missing.  Near the end of the story, an overall soothing and relaxing tune but with a tense melody to represent the finality, the game's story drawing to a close.
Just listen.  It starts out so calm, almost like music you would use in a dream. It gradually transitions to that tenseness primarily by slowly adding more instruments.  It all comes together in an epic climax.  Yet the tempo always stays pretty slow, keeping that relaxed feeling.
Brilliant.

snippet.textDisplay:
Very possibly some of the best VGM ever right here. To all the people hating on this piece, this is what the music symbolizes:

-A rememberance of all the missions that you've been through with your partner
-That same partner, who cares deeply for you, has joined you on your final mission
-The urgency of the mission at hand, which has been foretold to basically be a suicide mission
-The fact that you must journey onwards, as the world is in your hands

THIS IS DEEPER THAN YOU THINK.

You knew the end awaited you at the summit, you knew everything and everyone was counting on you, you knew Rayquaza was waiting. Hence, this song is amazing.

"OH MY GOD, THERE'S ANOTHER 10 FLOORS WE HAVE TO WALK THROUGH!"

"But..."

"SHUT UP AND MARCH, YOU MINDLESS YELLOW SQUIRREL! AND KEEP YOUR PAWS OFF THE STORE ITEMS. WHAT DID I TELL YOU ABOUT THE PSYCHOTIC KECLEONS?"

"But..."

"WHAT IS IT? ANOTHER MONSTER ROOM? A MIND NUMBING CUTSCENE VAGUELY RELATED TO THE PLOT?  YOUR AI FORGOT HOW TO WALK AROUND CORNERS AGAIN?"

"No! We're out of Big Apples, and we've been walking for a whole 5 minutes without eating!"

"Oh poopy." 

*dies of starvation*

I remember when I first bought this game. I got to Sky Tower, I loved it so much that I started humming it. When I got to the flute solo at 2:05-2:20, I started crying while humming, and I thought, "why am I crying?" Because it's so heartfelt. 
As always, Pokemon has the best music.

snippet.textDisplay: Wow...I'd have to say that Nintendo has done an interesting job composing some inspiring music for a game that's received poor reviews by game critics yet loved by the people who've ignored them and played it anyway. Ever since playing this game, I will never look at Pokemon the same way again. I mean it, this game blew me away in so many ways. Sky Tower is a hauntingly good song, especially since it's something you never forget...in a dreamy kind of way.
